MATCH_TOOL: Edit|Write
MATCH_PATTERN: apps/client/src/cartridges/games/.+Renderer\.tsx$
MATCH_CONTENT: (useCartridgeTheme|themeRef\.current|gameLoop\s*=\s*useCallback|colorKey|DEFAULT_CARTRIDGE_THEME|setTheme\()
ADVISORY: |
  Canvas theme-timing race — discovered in orbit's "no stars first time" bug:

  `useCartridgeTheme(ref)` returns DEFAULT_CARTRIDGE_THEME on first render.
  `useLayoutEffect` then reads the real CSS vars and calls setTheme(). The
  component re-renders with the resolved theme, and `themeRef.current` is
  refreshed.

  BUT — the `gameLoop` useCallback typically depends only on
  `[seed, difficulty, timeLimit]`, so it does NOT rebuild when theme
  updates. Any value captured inside gameLoop's outer scope stays stale
  for the life of the game.

  WRONG — captures whatever theme happened to be resolved at first paint:

      const gameLoop = useCallback(() => {
        const t = themeRef.current;  // snapshot — stale if useLayoutEffect
                                     // hadn't resolved yet
        const stars: Star[] = [];
        stars.push({ color: t.colors.gold, ... });  // baked forever
        function renderGame() {
          ctx.fillStyle = t.colors.bg;  // also stale
        }
      }, [seed, difficulty, timeLimit]);

  RIGHT — store theme keys (not resolved colors) on entities, and resolve
  via `themeRef.current` at point of use:

      interface Star { colorKey: ColorKey; /* ... */ }

      const gameLoop = useCallback(() => {
        // No `const t = themeRef.current` at this scope.
        stars.push({ colorKey: 'gold', ... });
        function renderGame() {
          const t = themeRef.current;           // per-frame live read
          ctx.fillStyle = t.colors.bg;
          // draw star:
          ctx.fillStyle = t.colors[star.colorKey];
        }
        function onCapture(star: Star) {
          // event-time — use themeRef.current directly
          screenFlash.trigger(withAlpha(themeRef.current.colors[star.colorKey], 0.2), 200);
        }
      });

  Also applies to TrailRenderer color callbacks and any other closure
  config passed into VFX primitives — they capture at construction
  time too.

  If you see "wrong colors on first load" / "default colors stuck" /
  "colors correct only after remount" in any canvas renderer, this is
  almost certainly the cause.
